The way to go is setting up a corresponding region of interest (ROI) by using [`cv::Rect`](https://docs.opencv.org/4.1.1/d2/d44/classcv_1_1Rect__.html). Since you already have your top left and bottom right locations as `cv::Points`, you get this more or less for free. Afterwards, just use - for example - [`cv::GaussianBlur`](https://docs.opencv.org/4.1.1/d4/d86/group__imgproc__filter.html#gaabe8c836e97159a9193fb0b11ac52cf1) only on that ROI. Using the C++ API, this approach works for a lot of OpenCV methods.

The code is quite simple, see the following snippet:

```c++
// (Just use your frame instead.)
cv::Mat image = cv::imread(&quot;path/to/your/image.png&quot;);

// Top left and bottom right cv::Points are already defined.
cv::Point topLeft = cv::Point(60, 40);
cv::Point bottomRight = cv::Point(340, 120);

// Set up proper region of interest (ROI) using a cv::Rect from the two cv::Points.
cv::Rect roi = cv::Rect(topLeft, bottomRight);

// Only blur image within ROI.
cv::GaussianBlur(image(roi), image(roi), cv::Size(51, 51), 0);
```

